BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Municipal Disaster Management & Smart City: A New Approach
DTSTART;TZID=Europe/Berlin:20260601T160000
DTEND;TZID=Europe/Berlin:20260601T173000
LOCATION:Ratsplenarsaal
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Rethinking digital sovereignty: Solid for interoperable & decentra
 lized data ecosystems!
DTSTART;TZID=Europe/Berlin:20260601T123000
DTEND;TZID=Europe/Berlin:20260601T130000
LOCATION:Room 270
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Digital Twin Leipzig – From buzzword to digital tool
DTSTART;TZID=Europe/Berlin:20260601T130000
DTEND;TZID=Europe/Berlin:20260601T133000
DESCRIPTION:The “Connected Urban Twins” funding project laid the found
 ation for the Leipzig Digital Twin in 2021. With the project now complete\
 , it is time for a brief summary. In this presentation\, GeodatenService L
 eipzig shows how the buzzword “digital twin” has given rise to concret
 e digital tools. We provide insights into the underlying technology and th
 e associated processes\, demonstrate the practical relevance using selecte
 d use cases\, and take a look at the next steps.
LOCATION:Room 270
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:AI-ready data – the foundation for real AI success
DTSTART;TZID=Europe/Berlin:20260601T133000
DTEND;TZID=Europe/Berlin:20260601T140000
DESCRIPTION:AI-ready data forms the indispensable basis for successful AI 
 initiatives\, as unclear data quality and a lack of transparency are among
  the most common reasons for project failure. A structured 360° view of t
 he data landscape reveals existing data treasures\, enables realistic use 
 case evaluations\, and provides clarity about potential and gaps. The FAIR
  criteria serve as a framework for sustainable and high-performance data q
 uality. By focusing on data maturity measures\, which range from data inve
 ntory and maturity assessment to the derivation of concrete measures\, the
  path to a robust database is systematically outlined. Supplemented by pra
 ctical experience and lessons learned\, we show how companies can optimize
  their data landscape in a targeted manner and thus ensure the future viab
 ility of data-driven AI projects.
LOCATION:Room 270
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Tomorrow's archiving – the data lifecycle in public administrati
 on
DTSTART;TZID=Europe/Berlin:20260601T143000
DTEND;TZID=Europe/Berlin:20260601T150000
DESCRIPTION:Public administration files and information go through a compl
 ex life cycle that is regulated by law from data creation to deletion or a
 rchiving and has been practiced for many years. But how do the legal requi
 rements that form the basis of the digital life cycle translate to digital
  administration? In this context\, the goal of electronic archiving is alw
 ays to generate open data. During the event\, which will feature a fluid t
 ransition between lectures and workshops\, the current status and developm
 ent goals will be clearly illustrated using the example of Leipzig's city 
 administration. The presentation will also explicitly address limiting fac
 tors such as legal requirements\, capacities\, interface developments\, an
 d expectations. The event will conclude with an interdisciplinary and open
 -ended discussion about prospects\, expectations\, and visions for the fut
 ure.
LOCATION:Sitzungssaal
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Modern OCR methods for handwriting and labels in the German-speaki
 ng context
DTSTART;TZID=Europe/Berlin:20260601T150000
DTEND;TZID=Europe/Berlin:20260601T153000
DESCRIPTION:Handwritten texts are not only found in historical archives\, 
 but also in modern industrial everyday life—for example\, on labels\, fo
 rms\, or protocols. However\, their automatic recognition poses particular
  challenges for data science\, especially in German-speaking countries\, w
 here freely available\, diverse handwriting datasets are rare. In this pre
 sentation\, we introduce two new\, publicly accessible datasets created fr
 om 852 handwritten German pages. Both datasets have been published on Zeno
 do and are freely available to researchers in linguistics\, computer scien
 ce\, and related disciplines.\nThe presentation shows how OCR models can b
 e successfully transferred to real-world applications. The contribution co
 mbines open data\, modern AI methods\, and concrete industrial use cases
 —and shows how handwriting recognition can advance both research and pra
 ctice today.
LOCATION:Sitzungssaal
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:The EOSC EDEN Re-Use Fitness Framework: What\, how\, for whom\, an
 d why archive?
DTSTART;TZID=Europe/Berlin:20260601T153000
DTEND;TZID=Europe/Berlin:20260601T160000
DESCRIPTION:Digital data is everywhere. In research\, it often serves as b
 oth the input and output of processes. But can and should this ever-growin
 g volume of data be preserved indefinitely? Who decides which data to pres
 erve and make available\, and based on what criteria? And what processes a
 re needed to ensure long-term archiving? The EU-funded project EOSC EDEN (
 European Open Science Cloud - Enhancing Digital Preservation Strategies at
  European and National Level) is developing a framework to support data id
 entification processes for long-term archiving. This presentation offers a
 n introduction to the challenges of long-term digital archiving of researc
 h data and summarizes the goals and results to date of the EOSC EDEN proje
 ct.
LOCATION:Sitzungssaal
END:VEVENT
